><br>
<br>
Daeldalus was an exercise run between 1973-1978 by the British Interplanetary Society.<br>
It was to design an interstellar unmanned one-way, non-stop flyby probe to Barnards Star in a travel time of 50 years.<br>
<br>
It was to use a (purely hypothetical) fusion engine exploding 250 micropellets of D/3He per second for four years using impinging electron beams.<br>
<br>
The Helium-3 and deuterium were to be scooped from Jupiter.<br>
<br>
To calculate the acceleration:<br>
================================<br>
A= acceleration in meters/second/second<br>
T= Time in seconds<br>
V= Velocity in meters per second<br>
<br>
Equation:     A=V/T<br>
<br>
(I will round numbers to make readability easier)<br>
<br>
V = 3.6 x 10^7 meters/second<br>
T=  1.3 x 10^8 seconds<br>
<br>
Puting these numbers in the equation gives us:<br>
<br>
A= 0.28 m/s/s =Acceleration of Daedalus<br>
==================================<br>
<br>
Gravity on Earth is 9.8 meters per second per second or<br>
1 Gee<br>
<br>
Therefore we see that Daedalus was to accelerate at 1/35th of a Gee.<br>
<br>
<br>
(A minor note: &quot;Thrust&quot; refers to how much force is being provided by an engine - not how fast the vehicle changes speed (called &quot;acceleration&quot;)<br>
A thrust of 100,000 pounds on an oceanliner would provide vastly less acceleration then a 100 pound thrust on a skateboarder.)<br>
<br>
<br>
yale<br>
-------------------------<br>
<br>
